			<abstract>
<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><p>An unusual regime for liquid-state nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) where the magnetic field strength is so low that the J-coupling (intramolecular spinspin) interactions dominate the spin Hamiltonian opens a new paradigm with applications in spectroscopy, quantum control, and in fundamental-physics experiments, including searches for well-motivated dark-matter candidates. An interesting possibility is to bring this kind of "extreme NMR" together with another one-single nuclear spin detected with a single-spin quantum sensor.</p><p>This would enable single-molecule J-spectroscopy.</p></div>
			</abstract>
		</profileDesc>
